<Layout
  title="Gap register"
  description="What PDTF cannot currently encode against the DBT Smart Data Guidebook — each gap verified against the committed TTL corpus, ranked by effort to close, with the closing move for each."
>
<PageMeta category="PDTF alignment" variant="warn" updated="Updated 2026-07-13" damaKa={["Data Governance", "Metadata Management"]} />

  <h1>Gap register</h1>

  <p class="lead">
    The asks in the <a href="/dbt-smart-data/pdtf-overlap">overlap analysis</a> that PDTF
    <strong>cannot currently encode</strong>. Every gap here was verified against the committed
    TTL corpus, not the ontology's layer plan. Ranked by effort to close — noting that the
    highest-<em>value</em> gap (G4) is mid-difficulty rather than hard, and the
    highest-<em>leverage</em> one (G3) is genuinely easy.
  </p>

  <div class="callout callout--key">
    <div class="callout__label">This is a draft register, not a ratified work plan</div>
    <p>
      These are engineering judgements from a read of the Guidebook drafts against the corpus.
      Anything that changes the ontology's shape — particularly <strong>G7</strong> (a
      <code>UseCase</code> class) and <strong>G6</strong> (modelling decisions and outcomes) —
      is a council question, not a unilateral one.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="ranked">The register</h2>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>#</th>
        <th>Gap</th>
        <th>Effort</th>
        <th>Why it matters</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr id="g1">
        <td><strong>G1</strong></td>
        <td><strong>Retention &amp; disposition terms.</strong> No way to say how long data is kept, or whether it is deleted <em>or anonymised</em> when its purpose ends.</td>
        <td>🟢 Very easy</td>
        <td>Closes Ch.4 Clause C outright. DPV already has the terms (<code>StorageDuration</code>, <code>Erase</code> vs <code>Anonymise</code>); binding them is a shape and a handful of triples.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr id="g2">
        <td><strong>G2</strong></td>
        <td><strong>Lifecycle stages with a responsible party.</strong> No vocabulary for collection → processing → sharing → retention → deletion, and no <code>hasResponsibleParty</code> per stage.</td>
        <td>🟢 Easy</td>
        <td>Closes Ch.4 §3.1.4 and Clause I ("responsibility transfers with the data"). DPV's processing terms map 1:1 onto the five stages; PROV supplies the actor attribution.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr id="g3">
        <td><strong>G3</strong></td>
        <td><strong>The origin facet: source / derived / insight / profiling.</strong> PDTF cannot say whether a datum was asserted or computed.</td>
        <td>🟢 Easy — <strong>do this first</strong></td>
        <td><strong>Cheap and unlocks three other gaps.</strong> Per house doctrine it ships as a <em>facet</em> (<code>sh:in</code> over a four-term SKOS scheme), not a subclass tree. It is the precondition for G4 and G6, and it delivers Ch.3's user-facing "verified / self-reported / derived" signal and Ch.4's transparency <em>data level</em>. Add the individual-linkable vs anonymised flag alongside it — that flag drives Ch.4's entire proportionality carve-out.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr id="g4">
        <td><strong>G4</strong></td>
        <td><strong>Derived-value provenance.</strong> A <em>property pack</em> is an aggregation of claims from many sources. If the pack is wrong but every source claim was right — who is accountable? PDTF models source claims well and derived claims not at all.</td>
        <td>🟡 Moderate — <strong>highest value</strong></td>
        <td><strong>OPDA's largest modelling gap and its largest liability gap are the same gap.</strong> The Ch.2 scoping paper says liability is hardest "where value is created through aggregation, transformation, or derived outputs" — and names property packs as its first test case. PROV is already adopted and SHACL-enforced on source claims; the work is choosing the granularity of derivation, requiring it on anything flagged "derived" (G3), and not confusing instance lineage with the existing <em>model</em> provenance chain.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr id="g5">
        <td><strong>G5</strong></td>
        <td><strong>Consent, delegation and the trust-signal cluster.</strong> No consent record, no delegated authority, no accreditation status, no audit event. Four missing artefacts that the Guidebook treats as one fabric.</td>
        <td>🟡 Moderate — <strong>largest hole</strong></td>
        <td>Chapter 1's data-holder role is <em>defined</em> by relying on a consent signal it must not re-interpret; PDTF cannot emit that signal. Chapter 3's dashboard requires active/expired/withdrawn permissions with history. Property is the <strong>delegation-heavy sector</strong> — LPA, probate, executors, divorce, co-ownership — and none of it is modelled. Needs ODRL (currently <em>zero</em> occurrences in the corpus). Full structure: <a href="/dbt-smart-data/user-lifecycle#consent-model">the consent-record model Ch.3 implies</a>.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr id="g6">
        <td><strong>G6</strong></td>
        <td><strong>AI-decision disclosure.</strong> "Whether automation or AI has been used" — and what it did to the outcome.</td>
        <td>🔴 Moderate-to-hard — genuinely new</td>
        <td>Hard not because the vocabulary is missing (DPV-AI is a near-exact fit and is <em>completely</em> unadopted) but because it requires PDTF to model <strong>decisions and outcomes</strong> — a new domain concept. The ontology today has no notion of an actor's <em>output</em> at all, only of property facts. This is a scope extension, and a council question.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr id="g7">
        <td><strong>G7</strong></td>
        <td><strong>Use-case as a first-class object.</strong> The Guidebook insists risk is assessed "at the use case and ecosystem level" — data combination, re-identification, inference, cumulative exposure. PDTF has no <code>UseCase</code> class and no risk-tier vocabulary.</td>
        <td>🔴 Hardest — structural</td>
        <td><strong>The deepest mismatch between the Guidebook's mental model and PDTF's.</strong> PDTF's entire model is property/dataset-centric; risk attaches to <em>data</em>, not to a <em>use of</em> data. Either PDTF adds the dimension (a council, and a real one) or it explicitly scopes itself out and hands use-case risk to scheme operators. Both are defensible. <em>Drifting between them is not.</em></td>
      </tr>
      <tr id="g8">
        <td><strong>G8</strong></td>
        <td><strong>Selective disclosure — and a false claim to retract.</strong> The proof suite is <code>Ed25519Signature2020</code> Linked Data Proofs (MUST, per the access specification), which does not support selective disclosure.</td>
        <td>🟡 Moderate — <strong>retraction is urgent</strong></td>
        <td>
          <strong>A live conformance failure, not a roadmap item.</strong> The Preamble's Principle 2
          and Chapter 1's Example D both require selective disclosure. Worse than a silent gap:
          <code>trust-framework/docs/governance.md</code> currently asserts
          <em>"Data minimization and selective disclosure enforced"</em> — <strong>a published claim
          OPDA cannot honour.</strong> Two actions, and the first is not optional:
          <strong>(1) withdraw that sentence</strong>; (2) adopt a BBS or SD-JWT proof suite — a
          trust-framework decision, not just an ontology one.
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr id="g9">
        <td><strong>G9</strong></td>
        <td><strong>Policy propagation on onward sharing.</strong> "Obligations travel with the data" (Ch.4 Clauses H &amp; I).</td>
        <td>🟡 Moderate</td>
        <td>Distinct from G5: <em>recording</em> a share and <em>binding the downstream policy</em> are different asks. ODRL's <code>nextPolicy</code>/<code>Duty</code> is exactly the primitive — and is the same reason the "confidentiality survives withdrawal" requirement (Ch.3 §2.3) cannot currently be expressed. A permission-only model cannot say <em>"you may no longer receive this, and you must still keep secret what you already received."</em></td>
      </tr>
      <tr id="g10">
        <td><strong>G10</strong></td>
        <td><strong>Data-quality metadata.</strong> A quality <em>framework</em> exists as policy; there is no DQV/ISO-25012 vocabulary attaching accuracy/completeness/currency to a value.</td>
        <td>🟢 Easy</td>
        <td>Converts an existing OPDA strength into a machine-checkable claim. We already over-deliver on the <em>substance</em> (six dimensions vs the Guidebook's vague ask); we just cannot yet <em>say</em> it in RDF.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr id="g11">
        <td><strong>G11</strong></td>
        <td><strong>Label coverage as a conformance property.</strong> Ch.4 requires outputs be human-readable <em>and</em> machine-readable.</td>
        <td>🟢 Trivial</td>
        <td>"We <em>can</em> label everything" is not the same as "everything <em>is</em> labelled". Ship a SHACL shape requiring <code>skos:prefLabel</code> on every concept and <code>rdfs:label</code> on every class/property, then assert coverage. <strong>A day's work that converts a soft claim into an auditable one.</strong></td>
      </tr>
      <tr id="g12">
        <td><strong>G12</strong></td>
        <td><strong>Dynamic trust signals.</strong> Participant suspension status, dynamic risk score, security incident notification, accreditation status change, credential validity — as <em>machine-readable</em> signals.</td>
        <td>🟡 Moderate — <strong>live deadline</strong></td>
        <td>
          <strong>This is Chapter 5's one and only data-standard ask</strong> (Position 3, "Trust
          should be dynamic") — and Chapter 5 is the chapter with the
          <strong>24 July 2026 review deadline</strong>. PDTF cannot emit a single one of these
          signals. Overlaps heavily with G5's accreditation-status half, but is listed separately
          because it is the one thing OPDA could commit to <em>in the Chapter 5 response</em>.
        </td>
      </tr>
      <tr id="g13">
        <td><strong>G13</strong></td>
        <td><strong>Assurance-level vocabulary.</strong> <code>opda:assuranceLevel</code> was <strong>removed</strong> on 2026-07-05 (ODR-0009 — "zero PDTF schema basis"). There is no assurance ladder in the corpus today.</td>
        <td>🟡 Moderate — needs a council</td>
        <td>
          Chapter 2 asks for a provenance schema carrying "issuer, inputs, timestamps,
          <strong>assurance level</strong>, revocation checks"; Chapter 1's CBOM needs an assurance
          <em>type</em> per credential. <strong>Do not re-add it by reflex</strong> — it was removed
          for a good reason (no schema basis), and re-adding it to satisfy DBT would repeat the
          original mistake. The right move is to ask whether an <em>evidential-provenance</em> scale
          (how authoritative is this fact about this house?) is warranted on its own merits, distinct
          from GPG 44/45 identity assurance. If it is, PDTF's mandatory claim provenance is the
          natural substrate — and <em>no other sector in the Guidebook has one</em>.
        </td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2 id="not-gaps">Things that look like gaps and are not</h2>

  <p>
    Equally important to record, so effort is not wasted defending against them or — worse —
    building them:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Liability allocation.</strong> PDTF does <em>not</em> need a <code>liableParty</code>
      property. Chapter 2 allocates liability <em>by rule</em>, not by data field. What the standard
      must supply is the <strong>evidence the rule operates on</strong>: who issued a signal, when,
      at what assurance level, and whether a status check was performed at the point of reliance.
      <strong>Encode the evidence, not the verdict.</strong>
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Security controls.</strong> FAPI, ISO 27001, encryption, incident response. These are
      scheme-operator obligations. PDTF's job is at most to <em>encode</em> that a participant
      holds a given certification — which is part of G5, not a separate security gap.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Model provenance ≠ instance provenance.</strong> PDTF's <code>dct:source</code> chain
      from every ontology term back to the JSON Schema leaf it was minted from is genuine,
      verifiable provenance — <em>of the model</em>. Claiming it satisfies Chapter 4's
      <em>instance-data lineage</em> ask would be a material overclaim that would not survive
      scrutiny by anyone who reads the ontology. (The good news, established while writing this
      register: PDTF <em>does</em> have real instance-level claim provenance —
      <code>prov:wasDerivedFrom</code> is SHACL-mandatory on every <code>opda:Claim</code>. The
      strength is real; just don't cite the wrong evidence for it.)
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="sequencing">Suggested sequencing</h2>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>G3 first</strong> (origin facet) — cheap, and G4 and G6 both depend on it.</li>
    <li><strong>G11, G1, G2, G10</strong> — a batch of easy wins that between them convert several soft conformance claims into auditable ones.</li>
    <li><strong>G4</strong> (derived-value provenance) — the highest-value gap, and the one property is being <em>watched</em> on. Chapter 2's scoping paper has property packs as its named test case, and its stated output is <em>template clauses</em>. There is an unusually clear invitation here to write the property accountability map rather than receive one.</li>
    <li><strong>G5</strong> (consent/delegation/trust signals) — the largest hole, and the one where the window may close. Every other sector already has an answer (Open Banking's consent dashboard, energy's RECCo Consumer Consent Solution). Property has nothing named. Either OPDA scopes consent into PDTF, or another body will own it for property — <em>and consent is where the scheme power sits.</em></li>
    <li><strong>G8's retraction is immediate and unconditional</strong> — the false selective-disclosure claim in <code>governance.md</code> should be withdrawn regardless of when the proof-suite work happens. The proof-suite decision itself needs the trust framework, so start that conversation early.</li>
    <li><strong>G12</strong> — the only gap with a <em>dated</em> deadline (Chapter 5, 24 July). Even if it cannot be closed by then, OPDA's Chapter 5 response should <em>name</em> it rather than let the review pass silently.</li>
    <li><strong>G6, G7, G13</strong> — council questions. Do not start unilaterally, and in G13's case do not simply reinstate what a council previously removed.</li>
  </ol>

  <div class="callout callout--warn">
    <div class="callout__label">Two of our own artefacts are wrong, independently of DBT</div>
    <p>
      Surfaced while compiling this register, and worth fixing whatever happens with the Guidebook:
    </p>
    <ol style="margin-bottom: 0;">
      <li>
        <strong>The legal-basis SHACL shape can never pass.</strong> <code>opda-agent-shapes.ttl</code>
        raises a <em>Violation</em> when special-category PII lacks <code>dpv:hasLegalBasis</code> —
        but the corpus asserts <code>opda:lawfulBasis</code> (with <code>dpv:</code> values).
        Conformant data would still fail. Either the shape or the predicate must change.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><code>governance.md</code> claims "selective disclosure enforced"</strong> — see G8.
        We cannot do it with an Ed25519-only proof suite.
      </li>
    </ol>
  </div>

